```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHTML(std::string const& markdown) {
    // Replace the markdown format with the corresponding HTML tags
    std::string html;

    std::regex rx_heading("([#]+)([\\w\\s]+)");
    std::regex rx_bold("([*]+)([\\w\\s]+)");
    std::regex rx_italic("([_]+)([\\w\\s]+)");
    std::regex rx_ul("([-]+)([\\w\\s]+)");
    std::regex rx_ol("([\\d]+\\.)([\\w\\s]+)");
    std::regex rx_code("(`+)([^`]+)");
    std::regex rx_inline_code("(`+)([^`]*)");

    bool match_heading = std::regex_search(markdown, rx_heading);
    bool match_bold = std::regex_search(markdown, rx_bold);
    bool match_italic = std::regex_search(markdown, rx_italic);
    bool match_ul = std::regex_search(markdown, rx_ul);
    bool match_ol = std::regex_search(markdown, rx_ol);
    bool match_code = std::regex_search(markdown, rx_code);
    bool match_inline_code = std::regex_search(markdown, rx_inline_code);

    if (match_heading) {
        std::smatch sm;
        std::regex_match(markdown, sm, rx_heading);

        std::string header_tag = "<h" + std::to_string(sm[1].length()) + ">";
        html += header_tag + sm[2] + "</h" + std::to_string(sm[1].length()) + ">";
    }

    if (match_bold) {
        std::smatch sm;
        std::regex_match(markdown, sm, rx_bold);

        html += "<strong>" + sm[2] + "</strong>";
    }

    if (match_italic) {
        std::smatch sm;
        std::regex_match(markdown, sm, rx_italic);

        html += "<em>" + sm[2] + "</em>";
    }

    if (match_ul) {
        std::smatch sm;
        std::regex_match(markdown, sm, rx_ul);

        html += "<ul>\n";
        html += markdownToHTML(sm[2]);
        html += "</ul>\n";
    }

    if (match_ol) {
        std::smatch sm;
        std::regex_match(markdown, sm, rx_ol);

        html += "<ol>\n";
        html += "<li>";
        html += markdownToHTML(sm[2]);
        html += "</li>\n";
        html += "</ol>\n";
    }

    if (match_code) {
        std::smatch sm;
        std::regex_match(markdown, sm, rx_code);

        html += "<code>" + sm[2] + "</code>";
    }

    if (match_inline_code) {
        std::smatch sm;
        std::regex_match(markdown, sm, rx_inline_code);

        html += "<code>" + sm[2] + "</code>";
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown_text = "*Hello, world!*";
    std::cout << "Original Markdown:\n" << markdown_text << "\n\nConverted HTML:\n";
    std::string html_text = markdownToHTML(markdown_text);
    std::cout << html_text;

    return 0;
}
```

This code defines a function `markdownToHTML` that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing html formatted text. The function uses regular expressions to match various markdown formats and replaces them with their corresponding HTML tags.

The `main` function demonstrates how to use the function by converting a simple example of markdown text into HTML.

Please note that this implementation is not complete and only covers a few basic markdown formats. You may need to extend the function to cover more complex or specific formatting requirements.

The snake game is a simple yet challenging game where the player controls a snake that grows in length as it eats food items. The goal of the game is to avoid colliding with the snake's own body or the walls of the playing field.

In this tutorial, we will create a simple snake game using C and SDL library. SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer) is a cross-platform library for creating 2D games and multimedia applications. It provides an easy-to-use interface for handling events, drawing graphics, playing sounds, and controlling the mouse and keyboard.

Here's an overview of what we will cover in this tutorial:

1. Setting up the project
2. Creating the game window and drawing the initial screen
3. Handling keyboard events and moving the snake
4. Checking for collisions between the snake and its own body or the walls
5. Adding food items and increasing the snake's length when it eats them
6. Adding a game over screen when the snake collides with something

To create the snake game, you'll need to have a C compiler installed on your system. If you're using Windows, we recommend using Dev-C++.

You'll also need to install the SDL library. You can download it from https://www.libsdl.org/download-2.0.php. Make sure to download the correct version for your operating system.

Once you have the SDL library installed, create a new folder for your project and add the following files:

1. `main.c` - This file contains the main function of the program and initializes the game window, handles events, draws the snake and food items, and checks for collisions.
2. `game_state.h` - This file defines the game states (START, PLAYING, GAMEOVER) and their corresponding functions.
3. `food.c` - This file contains the functions for drawing and updating the food items.
4. `snake.c` - This file contains the functions for drawing and updating the snake's position.
5. `gfx.h` - This file contains the definitions for the game's graphics.

Here's an overview of each file's content:

#### main.c

